Running a PyPy buildbot worker inside a container
=================================================

This is a fourth way to run a worker (see `README_BUILDSLAVE` for the others):
inside a prebuilt podman/docker image, using the same image as `start-slave.sh`
but without the benchmarking-specific bits (CPU pinning, fixed hostname).

The image ships the C build dependencies and a pinned PyPy2.7. The worker
itself runs in a virtualenv created on first start; `requirements.txt` in this
repo pins buildbot 0.8.8 and buildbot-slave.

Setup on the host
------------------

Create the worker BASEDIR as described in `README_BUILDSLAVE` (the
`buildslave create-slave BASEDIR MASTERHOST:PORT SLAVENAME PASSWORD` step). Lay
it out so the container sees it and `requirements.txt`:

    BASEDIR/
        slave/          # the created worker config (buildbot.tac etc.)
        requirements.txt

The container runs as UID:GID 1001:1001, so make sure BASEDIR is writable by
that user.

Starting the worker
-------------------

    IMAGE="ghcr.io/pypy/buildworker_x86_64@sha256:c9f502a46d9438a11b2cac9a27d10d9449bdbcfde11cb46b47fd569aa7b476ba"
    PYPY="/opt/pypy2.7-v7.3.22-linux64/bin"   # inside the container

    mkdir -p /tmp/buildworker
    chmod 1777 /tmp/buildworker

    podman run --rm -it \
        --name pypy-buildslave \
        --user 1001:1001 \
        --volume "$HOME/buildbot:/buildbot" \
        --volume /tmp/buildworker:/tmp \
        --workdir /buildbot/slave \
        --env HGDEMANDIMPORT=disable \
        "$IMAGE" \
        /bin/bash -c "
            set -euo pipefail
            PATH=\$PATH:$PYPY

            if [ -x /tmp/venv/bin/twistd ]; then
                . /tmp/venv/bin/activate
            else
                pypy -m virtualenv /tmp/venv
                . /tmp/venv/bin/activate
                pip install --no-cache-dir -r /buildbot/requirements.txt zstandard
            fi

            # buildbot 0.8.8 has no --nodaemon, so run twistd directly
            cd /buildbot/slave
            exec /tmp/venv/bin/twistd --nodaemon --pidfile= --python=buildbot.tac
        "

The venv lives in the `/tmp/buildworker` volume, so it survives restarts and is
only built the first time.

Stopping the worker
-------------------

    podman stop pypy-buildslave

`docker` can be substituted for `podman` throughout.
